{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17566035","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17566035"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:36:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:36:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18701"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18701","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18701"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.01,0.13,0.01,0.74]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11433"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76903"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11433","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11433"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18701"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62408"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"115"},{"type":"tags","id":"201"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"2589"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"11213"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26479"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43701"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76903","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76903"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 52-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with three months of progressive shortness of breath and dry cough. She reports difficulty climbing one flight of stairs. She has Raynaud phenomenon and joint pain in her hands. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She works as an accountant in an office environment with no exposure to dusts, fumes, or chemicals. She has never smoked. She has no pets at home and reports no water damage or mould in her house.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 85/min, blood pressure 125/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 94% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. There are fine crackles at both lung bases. Her hands show puffy fingers and thickened skin over the digits.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHigh-resolution CT chest shows bilateral ground glass opacities with fine reticulation in a predominantly peripheral and basal distribution.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Sarcoidosis","Cryptogenic organising pneumonia","Idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis","Hypersensitivity pneumonitis","Systemic sclerosis-associated interstitial lung disease"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features suggestive of systemic sclerosis including Raynaud phenomenon, puffy fingers with skin thickening, and imaging findings consistent with non-specific interstitial pneumonia (NSIP) pattern. \u003Cstrong\u003ESystemic sclerosis-associated interstitial lung disease\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with gradually progressive dyspnoea and dry cough, and NSIP is the most common radiological and histological pattern seen.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIdiopathic pulmonary fibrosis\u003C/strong\u003E typically affects older individuals and shows a usual interstitial pneumonia (UIP) pattern on imaging with honeycomb change, traction bronchiectasis, and minimal ground glass opacity. The presence of an underlying connective tissue disease makes this diagnosis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECryptogenic organising pneumonia\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents more acutely with flu-like symptoms and shows patchy consolidation or nodular opacities on imaging, often in a peribronchovascular distribution. It commonly occurs following a respiratory tract infection. The clinical and radiological features here are not consistent with this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypersensitivity pneumonitis\u003C/strong\u003E requires exposure to an inciting antigen, which is not present in this case given her office-based work and absence of exposures at home. The imaging pattern would typically show upper lobe predominant changes in chronic cases, rather than the basal distribution seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESarcoidosis\u003C/strong\u003E typically shows upper and mid-zone predominant changes with hilar lymphadenopathy on imaging. The presence of features suggesting systemic sclerosis makes this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEarly recognition of connective tissue disease-associated interstitial lung disease is important as immunosuppressive therapy may prevent progression to irreversible fibrosis. The presence of systemic features such as Raynaud phenomenon should prompt consideration of underlying connective tissue disease in any patient presenting with interstitial lung disease.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Connective tissue disease-associated interstitial lung disease commonly presents with progressive dyspnoea and dry cough.","High-resolution CT chest showing non-specific interstitial pneumonia pattern is characteristic of systemic sclerosis-associated lung disease.","Early recognition and immunosuppression can help prevent irreversible fibrosis in connective tissue disease-associated lung disease."],"references":["Jee AS, Sheehy R, Hopkins P, Corte TJ, Grainge C, Troy LK, Symons K, Spencer LM, Reynolds PN, Chapman S, De Boer S. Diagnosis and management of connective tissue disease\u2010associated interstitial lung disease in Australia and New Zealand: a position statement from the Thoracic Society of Australia and New Zealand. Respirology. 2021 Jan;26(1):23-51. Available at: https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1111/resp.13977","Vij R, Strek ME. Diagnosis and treatment of connective tissue disease-associated interstitial lung disease. Chest. 2013 Mar 1;143(3):814-24. Available at: https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0012369213601646"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62408"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18701"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62408","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62408"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-05T20:09:46+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-05T21:34:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11433"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76903"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"12","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4b","name":"Rheumatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"